<h3>The Compounding Effect</h3>
<p>Paid ads stop producing the moment you stop spending. A $5,000/month ad budget generates leads for exactly as long as you spend $5,000/month.</p>
<p>SEO content compounds. A blog post that costs $200 to produce can generate leads for years. First Page Sage projects that a consistent SEO program generates $385,000 in revenue in year 1, $1.2 million in year 2, and $3.3 million in year 3 (<a href="https://firstpagesage.com/reports/seo-roi-statistics-fc/">First Page Sage ROI data</a>).</p>
<p>The best approach: use paid ads for immediate lead flow while building your SEO pipeline. Once organic traffic reaches critical mass (usually 12 to 18 months), shift budget from paid to organic and keep the leads flowing at a fraction of the cost.</p>
<h3>Publishing Frequency Matters</h3>
<p>Companies publishing 16 to 20 blog posts per month generate 3 times more leads than companies publishing 4 or fewer (<a href="https://wpforms.com/lead-generation-statistics-and-trends/">WPForms</a>). Brands with active blogs generate 68% more leads overall.</p>
<p>Volume alone is not the answer. Quality and intent targeting matter. But frequency accelerates the compounding effect. More indexed pages = more keyword coverage = more entry points for potential leads. Use a <a href="/blog/content-marketing-strategy/">content marketing strategy</a> that balances quantity with quality.</p>
